    <item>
      <title>The true cost of game piracy: 20 percent of revenue, according to a new study</title>
      <author>
          Kyle Orland
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/the-true-cost-of-game-piracy-20-percent-of-revenue-according-to-a-new-study/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/civis/threads/the-true-cost-of-game-piracy-20-percent-of-revenue-according-to-a-new-study.1503455/</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/the-true-cost-of-game-piracy-20-percent-of-revenue-according-to-a-new-study/</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 10 Oct 2024 17:08:23 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="post-content post-content-double text-xl lg:pl-[72px]"&gt;                                                         &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="" name="page-1" data-page="1" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/the-true-cost-of-game-piracy-20-percent-of-revenue-according-to-a-new-study/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;Throughout the game industry's short history, there's been ample debate about how much piracy actually impacts a game's legitimate sales. On one side, some publishers &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2010/09/software-piracy-and-job-growth-a-zero-sum-game/"&gt;try to argue&lt;/a&gt; that every single pirated download should count as a "lost sale" that they would have logged in a theoretical piracy-free world. On the other side, some wiseacres argue that most pirates would never consider paying for a legitimate version of the game in the first place or that piracy can actually &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/09/eu-study-finds-piracy-doesnt-hurt-game-sales-may-actually-help/"&gt;be useful&lt;/a&gt; as a &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/09/how-one-game-developer-is-making-the-pirate-bay-work-for-him/"&gt;word-of-mouth promotional tool&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While the true effect of piracy on sales revenue is likely somewhere between those two extremes, piracy's precise financial impact on a game has always been hard to nail down. Now, though, a recently published study uses &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/10/denuvos-drm-ins-now-being-cracked-within-hours-of-release/"&gt;post-release cracks&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2023/07/denuvo-wants-to-convince-you-its-drm-isnt-evil/"&gt;Denuvo's DRM protections&lt;/a&gt; as a sort of natural experiment on games sales in pre- and post-piracy worlds. The results "imply an average proportionate loss of revenue of around 19 percent in each week of release if a crack is available," according to the study, suggesting that effective DRM can actually have a significant impact on a publisher's bottom line.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;The data dance&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;In &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9"&gt;"The Revenue Effects of Denuvo Digital Rights Management on PC Video Games,"&lt;/a&gt; published in the peer-reviewed journal &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/entertainment-computing"&gt;Entertainment Computing&lt;/a&gt;, UNC research associate &lt;a href="https://uncipc.org/index.php/people/william-volckmann/"&gt;William Volckmann&lt;/a&gt; examines 86 different Denuvo-protected games initially released on Steam between September 2014 and the end of 2022. That sample includes many games where Denuvo protection endured for at least 12 weeks (when new sales tend to drop off to "negligible" amounts for most games) and many others where earlier cracks allowed for widespread piracy at some point.&lt;/p&gt;                                   &lt;div class="ars-interlude-container in-content-interlude"&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="post-content post-content-double text-xl lg:pl-[72px]"&gt;                       &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2055578 align-center"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;             &lt;div class="ars-lightbox-item"&gt;               &lt;a data-pswp-width="1440" data-pswp-height="894" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-300x186.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-640x397.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-768x477.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-1536x954.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-2048x1272.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-980x609.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-1440x894.jpg 1440w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-1440x894.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in"&gt;                 &lt;img decoding="async" width="2333" height="1449" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1.jpg 2333w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-300x186.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-640x397.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-768x477.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-1536x954.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-2048x1272.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-980x609.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy1-1440x894.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2333px) 100vw, 2333px"&gt;               &lt;/a&gt;               &lt;div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2055578"&gt;                 A majority of Denuvo games studied remained uncracked during the crucial 12-week sales window after release.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;                     Credit:                                           &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9" target="_blank"&gt;Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann&lt;/a&gt;                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/div&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       A majority of Denuvo games studied remained uncracked during the crucial 12-week sales window after release.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                        &lt;a class="caption-credit-link text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-300" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9"&gt;                      Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann                        &lt;/a&gt;                   &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Crucially, the presence and/or specific timing of a crack's availability couldn't be effectively predicted by characteristics like pricing or critical review scores. That makes the existence of a crack "a practically exogenous event" that can be used to effectively segregate a game's revenues in a no-piracy world (i.e., before the Denuvo crack is available) and a piracy-filled world (i.e., after the crack's release). The variable timing of different crack releases also helps the relative analysis, since "revenue is highest close to the release date, and therefore a crack that appears close to the release date has a disproportionately large effect on revenue," Volckmann writes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, the &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/series/steam-gauge/"&gt;lack of good publicly available sales data&lt;/a&gt; for most games makes it difficult to measure these revenue effects directly. To estimate a Steam game's relative sales decline in each week after release, Volckmann uses a proxy that combines the number of new Steam user reviews and, for single-player narrative games, the game's average active player count. While Volckmann acknowledges that these imperfect estimates represent "the biggest limitation of this study," any estimated biases away from actual sales data seem likely to cancel out across the various games in the sample.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="record-pageview" name="page-2" data-page="2" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/the-true-cost-of-game-piracy-20-percent-of-revenue-according-to-a-new-study/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;h2&gt;“The no-crack counterfactual”&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;After applying some complex statistical models to the underlying data, Volckmann finds that, unsurprisingly, relative revenues in the weeks following a crack's release are lower than the baseline expectation for uncracked games in the same time period. These negative effects of a crack on revenues—which are highly statistically significant (p&amp;lt;0.01)—"impl[ies] that the appearance of a crack reduces revenue relative to the no-crack counterfactual," Volckmann writes.&lt;/p&gt;                               &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="post-content post-content-double text-xl lg:pl-[72px]"&gt;                       &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2055577 align-center"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;             &lt;div class="ars-lightbox-item"&gt;               &lt;a data-pswp-width="1440" data-pswp-height="737" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-300x154.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-640x328.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-768x393.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-1536x786.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-2048x1048.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-980x502.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-1440x737.jpg 1440w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-1440x737.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in"&gt;                 &lt;img decoding="async" width="2333" height="1194" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2.jpg 2333w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-300x154.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-640x328.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-768x393.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-1536x786.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-2048x1048.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-980x502.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy2-1440x737.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2333px) 100vw, 2333px"&gt;               &lt;/a&gt;               &lt;div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2055577"&gt;                 The longer a game's DRM lasts, the fewer new sales are left to be affected by piracy.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;                     Credit:                                           &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9" target="_blank"&gt;Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann&lt;/a&gt;                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/div&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       The longer a game's DRM lasts, the fewer new sales are left to be affected by piracy.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                        &lt;a class="caption-credit-link text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-300" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9"&gt;                      Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann                        &lt;/a&gt;                   &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Just how much money a publisher can expect to lose from a Denuvo crack, though, depends heavily on how quickly the game is cracked, Volckmann finds. A Denuvo-protected game cracked in the first week after release can expect to make about 20 percent less revenue than if the DRM had remained in place, according to the study, while a crack six weeks after a game's release only costs an estimated 5 percent of theoretical total revenue. After 12 weeks, new sales are so negligible that "developers could eventually remove unpopular DRM schemes with minimal losses (and possible gains from strongly DRM-averse consumers)," Volckmann suggests (and some publishers &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/12/after-cracks-developers-remove-denuvo-drm-from-their-games/"&gt;have done just that&lt;/a&gt; after Denuvo is no longer effectively protecting new sales).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Volckmann's data lines up with public statements that Denuvo-maker Irdeto has made regarding the need for DRM to protect a game's crucial post-launch window. "We don't position Denuvo Anti Tamper as being uncrackable—no anti piracy solution is," Denuvo VP of Sales Robert Hernandez &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/02/denuvo-our-cracked-re7-protection-is-still-better-than-nothing/"&gt;told Ars in 2017&lt;/a&gt;. "However, our goal is to keep each title safe from piracy during the crucial initial sales window when most of the sales are made."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2055576 align-center"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;             &lt;div class="ars-lightbox-item"&gt;               &lt;a data-pswp-width="1440" data-pswp-height="740" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-300x154.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-640x329.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-768x395.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-1536x790.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-2048x1053.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-980x504.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-1440x740.jpg 1440w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-1440x740.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in"&gt;                 &lt;img decoding="async" width="2424" height="1246" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3.jpg 2424w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-300x154.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-640x329.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-768x395.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-1536x790.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-2048x1053.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-980x504.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/denuvostudy3-1440x740.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2424px) 100vw, 2424px"&gt;               &lt;/a&gt;               &lt;div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2055576"&gt;                 The difference between a week 1 Denuvo crack and a week 6 crack can be significant amounts of revenue.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;                     Credit:                                           &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9" target="_blank"&gt;Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann&lt;/a&gt;                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/div&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       The difference between a week 1 Denuvo crack and a week 6 crack can be significant amounts of revenue.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                        &lt;a class="caption-credit-link text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-300" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1875952124002532?dgcid=author#fn9"&gt;                      Entertainment Computing / William Volckmann                        &lt;/a&gt;                   &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Overall, according to Volckmann's data, Denuvo is doing just that. The median Denuvo-protected games lose almost no sales to piracy, Volckmann suggests, because the protection "more often than not" goes uncracked in that initial 12-week window. In a world with no DRM, on the other hand, Volckmann projects those games could expect 20 percent less revenue at the median.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Whatever you think of DRM schemes like Denuvo, the potential to protect against that kind of revenue hit is something that major publishers might find hard to ignore. And there are signs that Denuvo's protection is becoming more crack-resistant in recent months; the CrackWatch subreddit &lt;a href="https://old.reddit.com/r/CrackWatch/comments/p9ak4n/crack_watch_games/"&gt;lists 28 Denuvo-protected games released so far in 2024&lt;/a&gt;, 26 of which remain uncracked and two of which were cracked well outside the 12-week release window. As we see in this study, that kind of robust protection can be worth a significant amount to a piracy-wary game publisher.&lt;/p&gt;                                &lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Captain Nemo swashbuckles his way under the sea in Nautilus trailer</title>
      <author>
          Jennifer Ouellette
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/culture/2024/10/nautilus-trailer-explores-captain-nemos-origins/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/civis/threads/nautilus-trailer-explores-captain-nemo%E2%80%99s-origins.1503453/</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://arstechnica.com/culture/2024/10/nautilus-trailer-explores-captain-nemos-origins/</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 10 Oct 2024 15:21:44 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="post-content post-content-double text-xl lg:pl-[72px]"&gt;                                                         &lt;figure class="ars-video"&gt;&lt;div class="relative" style="aspect-ratio: 1.7818181818182 auto;"&gt;&lt;iframe class="absolute left-0 top-0 block h-full w-full object-cover" allow="fullscreen" loading="lazy" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2HxWthmp9HU?start=0&amp;amp;wmode=transparent"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       Shazad Latif stars as Captain Nemo in Prime Video's new series, &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;.            &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/figure&gt; &lt;p&gt;Captain Nemo is one of 19th-century French novelist Jules Verne's most captivating fictional characters, appearing in &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twenty_Thousand_Leagues_Under_the_Seas"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (1870) and &lt;em&gt;The Mysterious Island&lt;/em&gt; (1875). Prime Video is bringing us a 10-episode series exploring Nemo's origin story, loosely based on the former, called &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautilus_(TV_series)"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, premiering in a couple of weeks. The official trailer just dropped, and it has all the swashbuckling, deep sea diving adventures, and exotic sea creatures one would expect from a classic Verne tale—including that infamous giant squid and a plucky romantic interest for good measure.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(Minor spoilers for the novels below.)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In Verne's novels, Nemo is a mysterious figure also known as Prince Dakkar, who lost his kingdom and his family in the Indian Rebellion of 1857. He devotes himself to science and builds an electrically powered submersible ship called the &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;, salvaging gold bullion from shipwrecks to fund his travels, occasionally coming to the aid of people in need (a pearl diver under a shark attack or castaways in need of rescue). He is well-read, has a Western education, and is fluent in several languages, as well as being a gifted engineer. And he appreciates the fine arts.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The same broad outlines seem largely intact in the depiction of Nemo in the TV series &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;. Disney+ originally commissioned the British adventure drama and tapped James Dormer as showrunner, but it decided not to move forward after filming was complete. AMC and Prime Video stepped in and acquired distribution rights in the US and Canada (AMC) and the UK and Ireland (Prime Video).&lt;/p&gt;                                   &lt;div class="ars-interlude-container in-content-interlude"&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="post-content post-content-double text-xl lg:pl-[72px]"&gt;                       &lt;p&gt;The 10-part series is set in 1857, when the power of the British East India Company was at its peak, bolstered by its own private army and navy. The Company is secretly building a massive submersible ship in Kalpani, India, using slave labor from the colonial prisons. Nemo (Shazad Latif, who played Ash Tyler in &lt;em&gt;Star Trek: Discovery&lt;/em&gt;) is among those prisoners and just happened to design the engine of the &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;, so he knows his way around the ship.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2055542 align-none"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;             &lt;div class="ars-lightbox-item"&gt;               &lt;a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="805" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-980x657.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in"&gt;                 &lt;img decoding="async" width="1200" height="805" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="19th century steampunk style submarine" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/nautilus6-980x657.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px"&gt;               &lt;/a&gt;               &lt;div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2055542"&gt;                 Behold the latest incarnation of the &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;                     Credit:                                           YouTube/Prime Video                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/div&gt;             &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       Behold the latest incarnation of the &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       YouTube/Prime Video                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Nemo orchestrates an uprising and escapes to sea with the &lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt;. The East India Company naturally sends its own forces in hot pursuit to reclaim their submersible and execute Nemo. Meanwhile, "Nemo and his motley crew sail beneath the seas on a mission of retribution and vengeance to utterly destroy the power of the Company... and the Company itself."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In addition to Latif, the cast includes Georgia Flood as Humility Lucas; Thierry Fremont as Gustave Benoit; Pacharo Mzembe as Boniface; Damian Garvey as Director Crawley; Richard E. Grant as the leader of the Karajaan; Cameron Cuffe as Captain Pitt; Jacob Collins-Levy as Captain Youngblood; and Luke Arnold as Captain Billy Millais. Anna Torv will guest-star in the penultimate episode as Revna.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Nautilus&lt;/em&gt; debuts on Prime Video on October 25, 2024.&lt;/p&gt;                                &lt;/div&gt;</description>
